safety_criterion:
Header comment requirements: Before the executable code of each module, a section of comment text must be provided to describe the following content:
Module name comment: Identify the module's name, version number, entry point, developer's name, organization, and development date; if modified, also identify the modifier's name, organization, and modification date;
Module function comment: Explain the purpose and function of the module;
Input/Output comment: Describe the input/output file names used by the module, indicating whether each file inputs into or outputs from the module, or both;
Parameter comment: Describe the name, data type, size, physical unit, and usage of all parameters required by the module, explain the name, data type, size, physical unit, and usage method of global variables applicable to the module, and describe the return value of the module;
Call comment: List all called module names within the module and all modules that call this module;
Constraint comment: List all special factors limiting the module's execution characteristics;
Exception termination comment: List all exceptional return conditions and actions;
Method comment: Describe the methods used by the module to achieve its functions; for brevity, reference documentation describing these methods may also be cited;
External environment and resource comment: Describe the external operating environment and resources used by the module, such as operating systems, compilers, assembly languages, CPUs, memory, registers, stacks, etc.

Internal comment requirements: Within the module, at least statements that conditionally change data values or execution order (i.e., branch transfer statements, input/output statements, loop statements, call statements) must be commented. These comments should not disrupt the clarity of the module, i.e., they should conform to the program's indentation format. Specific commenting methods are as follows:
Branch transfer statements: Indicate the reason for the execution action;
Input/output statements: Indicate the nature of the processed file or record;
Loop statements: Explain the execution reason and exit conditions;
Call statements: Describe the reason for the call and the functionality of the called module.

Install an anti-virus database and perform virus scanning and removal. Prevent viruses from causing data security issues.
 Server Protection: Perform virus scanning and removal on servers running various operating systems;
 Client Protection: Perform virus scanning and removal on various desktop operating systems;
 Anti-Virus Management Functionality: Centrally manage anti-virus software across all clients, providing centralized distribution of policies, updates, configurations, management, and statistics functions to enable centralized monitoring of virus prevention.

Autonomously select a corresponding series of backup files (i.e., the recovery sequence) based on previous backups and the target recovery time, using numerical order to represent the sequence. For example:
1A full backup file at time t;
2A change backup file from time t to time k;
3A log backup file from time k to the current recovery time s.
These three backup files and their numbers form a recovery sequence that can restore data to its state at time s.
